 Plan: Fix Windows Update SOAP discovery to find installable build packages (ESDs)
                                                                                                  
 Context

 Windows Update serves full feature-upgrade packages for Windows 11 (e.g. 24H2 build 26100.8313)
 as a set of .esd/.cab files hosted on Microsoft's CDN at
 tlu.dl.delivery.mp.microsoft.com/filestreamingservice/files/. These CDN URLs are obtained
 natively via the GetExtendedUpdateInfo2 (EUI2) SOAP call — no intermediary like UUP dump is
 required. Once a client has the CDN URLs it can:

 1. Download any individual file with a plain curl GET (no auth, no decryption — URLs are
 time-limited pre-signed tokens).
 2. Assemble a bootable ISO using standard open-source tools available on Linux and macOS:
 cabextract, wimlib-imagex, chntpw, genisoimage/mkisofs.

 UUP dump itself uses this same CDN — its get.php?aria2=2 endpoint just emits an aria2
 download script that points at these same tlu.dl.delivery.mp.microsoft.com URLs.

 Our native implementation currently returns 0 CDN file URLs from EUI2 for all builds.
 Root cause analysis against the PHP reference source at git.uupdump.net/uup-dump/api
 reveals three bugs in our Go implementation that prevent both build discovery and file
 URL resolution.

 ---
 Root Cause Analysis

 Bug 1 — Wrong product prefix in buildProductsString (fetch.go:474)

 Our code emits Client.OS.rs2.{arch} for SKU 48 (Windows Professional). The PHP reference
 uses Client.OS.{arch}. The .rs2 suffix was a Redstone 2 era name (circa 2017); modern WU
 endpoints no longer map it to the same update catalogue. This causes our SyncUpdates request
 to be offered a different (or empty) set of updates than the PHP reference would receive.

 Fix: Change the fallback product prefix from "Client.OS.rs2" → "Client.OS".

 Bug 2 — Wrong base build for discovery: we claim to be on 24H2 already

 Our default build = "10.0.26100.0" means we're claiming to be on Windows 11 24H2 baseline.
 In Retail ring, WU responds with 0 updates (we're already current). In Dev ring, WU offers the
 NEXT feature update (26300.x) — a pre-release upgrade, not a stable 24H2 installation package.

 The PHP reference defaults its base build to "10.0.16251.0" — an ancient Windows 10 Insider
 build. This makes WU think the device needs upgrading all the way to the latest stable release
 (e.g., Windows 11 24H2 build 26100.8313), and returns that as a leaf update with a proper
 UpdateID that EUI2 will resolve to CDN file URLs.

 Fix: Add a CheckBuild field to wuproto.FetchRequest. When empty, default to
 "10.0.16251.0". Use CheckBuild as the version in OSVersion, AppVer, MediaVersion,
 WuClientVer device attribute fields and as the version in the Products string primary
 product V= parameter. The existing Build field (currently controlling syncCurrentOnly)
 becomes the optional target-build filter.

 Bug 3 — EUI2 device attributes hardcoded to a stale Windows 10 build

 fileurl.go:37 hardcodes buildDeviceAttributes("amd64", "Retail", "10.0.19041.1", ...) for
 every EUI2 call regardless of the update being queried. The PHP reference uses device attributes
 with OSVersion matching the found build (e.g., 10.0.26100.8313) and the original ring
 used in SyncUpdates. Mismatched attributes cause the fe3cr endpoint to return an empty
 <GetExtendedUpdateInfo2Result/>.

 Fix: Add Arch, Ring, Build fields to wuproto.FileURLRequest. The SOAPClient
 will build EUI2 device attributes from those fields instead of the hardcoded values.
 winupdate/builds.go and winupdate/files.go will pass the build's arch/ring/build into
 FileURLRequest when they call GetFileURLs.

