 ---
 Implementation Steps

 Step 1 �� Fix product prefix (fetch.go)

 // wuproto/soap/fetch.go  ~line 474
 productPrefix, ok := skuToProduct[sku]
 if !ok {
     productPrefix = "Client.OS"  // was "Client.OS.rs2"
 }

 Step 2 — Add CheckBuild to FetchRequest + wire through fetch.go

 wuproto/interface.go:
 type FetchRequest struct {
     Arch        Arch
     Ring        Ring
     Flight      Flight
     Build       string  // empty = latest (was the build version)
     CheckBuild  string  // base OS version device claims to be on; default "10.0.16251.0"
     SKU         int
     Type        BuildType
 }

 wuproto/soap/fetch.go — fetchUpdates():
 checkBuild := req.CheckBuild
 if checkBuild == "" {
     checkBuild = "10.0.16251.0"  // PHP reference default
 }
 // Use checkBuild everywhere previously using `build` in device attrs + products:
 deviceAttrs := buildDeviceAttributes(arch, ring, checkBuild, "", sku, buildType)
 products    := buildProductsString(arch, ring, checkBuild, sku)

 The Products string primary product now becomes:
 fmt.Sprintf("PN=Client.OS.%s&Branch=%s&PrimaryOSProduct=1&Repairable=1&V=%s&ReofferUpdate=1",
     arch, branch, checkBuild)

 Step 3 — Fix EUI2 device attributes

 wuproto/interface.go:
 type FileURLRequest struct {
     UpdateID string
     Revision int
     // Arch/Ring/Build should match the update's origin context for EUI2.
     // If empty, sensible defaults are used.
     Arch  Arch
     Ring  Ring
     Build string
 }

 wuproto/soap/fileurl.go — getFileURLs():
 arch  := string(req.Arch);  if arch == ""  { arch = "amd64" }
 ring  := string(req.Ring);  if ring == ""  { ring = "Retail" }
 build := req.Build;         if build == "" { build = "10.0.26100.0" }
 deviceAttrs := buildDeviceAttributes(arch, ring, build, "", 48, "Production")

 Step 4 — Propagate arch/ring/build into FileURLRequest callers

 winupdate/files.go — GetFiles() when req.WithURLs:
 // Pull arch/ring/build from the catalog Build record so EUI2 gets correct context.
 b, err := s.store.GetBuild(ctx, req.UUID)
 // ...
 urls, err := s.wu.GetFileURLs(ctx, wuproto.FileURLRequest{
     UpdateID: req.UUID,
     Revision: req.Revision,
     Arch:     wuproto.Arch(b.Arch),
     Ring:     wuproto.Ring(b.Ring),
     Build:    b.Build,
 })

 winupdate/download.go — StreamDownload(): same pattern; look up build from catalog.

 Step 5 — Expose check_build in the HTTP API and CLI

 api/handlers/updates.go:
 type fetchRequest struct {
     Arch       string `json:"arch"`
     Ring       string `json:"ring"`
     Flight     string `json:"flight"`
     Build      string `json:"build"`
     CheckBuild string `json:"check_build"`  // new
     SKU        int    `json:"sku"`
 }

 cmd/winupdate/commands/fetch.go:
 fetchCmd.Flags().String("check-build", "10.0.16251.0",
     "base OS version the WU client claims to be on (controls which upgrades are offered)")

 ---
 Validation

 Expected outcome after fixes

 # 1. Fetch Windows 11 24H2 packages from Retail by starting from an old base
 docker compose exec winupdate winupdate fetch \
     --db /data/winupdate.db \
     --arch amd64 --ring Retail \
     --check-build 10.0.16251.0
 # Expected: ≥1 new build, title contains "Windows 11" and build "26100.x"

 # 2. List builds — should see 26100.x in Retail/amd64
 curl --cert certs/client.crt --key certs/client.key --cacert certs/ca.crt \
     https://localhost:8443/v1/builds | jq '.data[] | {build, arch, ring}'

 # 3. Get file URLs via EUI2 for the new build UUID
 UUID=$(curl ... https://localhost:8443/v1/builds | jq -r '.data[0].uuid')
 REV=$(curl ... https://localhost:8443/v1/builds/$UUID | jq -r '.data.revision')
 curl ... "https://localhost:8443/v1/builds/$UUID/files?with_urls=true&revision=$REV" \
     | jq '.data[] | {name, size_bytes, url}'
 # Expected: ≥1 file entry with a non-empty .url field (CDN URL)

 # 4. Poke CDN URL directly with curl (proves URL is valid, no decryption needed)
 CDN_URL=$(curl ... | jq -r '.data[0].url')
 curl -I "$CDN_URL"
 # Expected: HTTP 200 with Content-Length, Content-Type: application/octet-stream

 # 5. Download the smallest ESD file via the REST API
 curl --cert certs/client.crt --key certs/client.key --cacert certs/ca.crt \
     -o downloads/windows11.esd \
     "https://localhost:8443/v1/builds/$UUID/files/windows11.esd/download?revision=$REV"
 # Expected: file saved to disk, SHA1 matches value from EUI2 response

 What "Windows 11 24H2 (26100.8313) amd64" actually is

 A feature-upgrade package served by Windows Update when a device claims to be on an old build.
 It is distributed as a set of ESD files (one per edition — Home, Pro, Education, etc.), language
 pack cabs, Features-on-Demand cabs, and driver cabs — totalling ~10 GB for a full en-us set
 with core + professional editions.

 The CDN URLs from EUI2 point directly to
 tlu.dl.delivery.mp.microsoft.com/filestreamingservice/files/<sha1>?P1=…&P2=…&P3=…&P4=….
 No decryption is required — the files are raw ESDs/cabs accessible with a plain curl GET.

 ISO assembly

 Once the ESD/cab files are downloaded, a bootable ISO can be built on Linux/macOS using:

 ┌────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┐
 │          Tool          │             Purpose              │
 ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
 │ cabextract             │ Extract cabinet (.cab) archives  │
 ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
 │ wimlib-imagex          │ Export WIM images from ESD files │
 ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
 │ chntpw                 │ Patch registry in boot.wim       │
 ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
 │ genisoimage or mkisofs │ Write final bootable ISO         │
 └────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────┘

 These are available on Debian/Ubuntu (apt-get install cabextract wimtools chntpw genisoimage)
     A feature-upgrade package served by Windows Update when a device claims to be on an old build.
     It is distributed as a set of ESD files (one per edition — Home, Pro, Education, etc.),
     language
     pack cabs, Features-on-Demand cabs, and driver cabs — totalling ~10 GB for a full en-us set
     with core + professional editions.
                                                                         
     The CDN URLs from EUI2 point directly to                                       
     tlu.dl.delivery.mp.microsoft.com/filestreamingservice/files/<sha1>?P1=…&P2=…&P3=…&P4=….
     No decryption is required — the files are raw ESDs/cabs accessible with a plain curl GET.      

     ISO assembly                                                                

     Once the ESD/cab files are downloaded, a bootable ISO can be built on Linux/macOS using:
                                 
     ┌────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┐
     │          Tool          │             Purpose              │
     ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
     │ cabextract             │ Extract cabinet (.cab) archives  │
     ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤         
     │ wimlib-imagex          │ Export WIM images from ESD files │
     ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
     │ chntpw                 │ Patch registry in boot.wim       │
     ├────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
     │ genisoimage or mkisofs │ Write final bootable ISO         │
     └────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────┘

     These are available on Debian/Ubuntu (apt-get install cabextract wimtools chntpw genisoimage)
     and macOS via Homebrew. ISO assembly is a follow-on feature; the three SOAP bug fixes are
     the prerequisite that unlocks the CDN URLs.

     Additional housekeeping tasks (separate from SOAP fixes)

     1. .gitignore — add /data/, /certs/, /downloads/, *.db, winupdate binary
     2. README.md — rewrite to describe the current native WU SOAP platform (not the old
     UUP dump JSON API wrapper SDK that the existing README documents)

                   